# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hdmi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In computer networking, **Fast Ethernet** physical layers carry traffic at the nominal rate of 100 Mbit/s.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Of the Fast Ethernet physical layers, **100BASE-TX** is by far the most common.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet was introduced in 1995 as the **IEEE 802.3u** standard and remained the fastest version of Ethernet for three years before the introduction of Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The acronym *GE/FE* is sometimes used for devices supporting both standards.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The *100* in the media type designation refers to the transmission speed of 100 Mbit/s, while the *BASE* refers to baseband signaling.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The letter following the dash (*T* or *F*) refers to the physical medium that carries the signal (twisted pair or fiber, respectively), while the last character (*X*, *4*, etc.) refers to the line code method used.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet is sometimes referred to as **100BASE-X**, where *X* is a placeholder for the FX and TX variants.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] IEEE 802.2 refers to Fast Ethernet collectively as **100BASE-T**, including fiber variants.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet is an extension of the 10-megabit Ethernet standard.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It runs on twisted pair or optical fiber cable in a star wired bus topology, similar to the IEEE standard 802.3i called 10BASE-T, itself an evolution of 10BASE5 (802.3) and 10BASE2 (802.3a).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet devices are generally backward compatible with existing 10BASE-T systems, enabling plug-and-play upgrades from 10BASE-T.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Most switches and other networking devices with ports capable of Fast Ethernet can perform autonegotiation, sensing a piece of 10BASE-T equipment and setting the port to 10BASE-T half duplex if the 10BASE-T equipment cannot perform autonegotiation itself.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The standard specifies the use of CSMA/CD for media access control.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] A full-duplex mode is also specified, and in practice, modern networks use Ethernet switches and operate in full-duplex mode, even as legacy devices that use half duplex still exist.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] A Fast Ethernet adapter can be logically divided into a media access controller (MAC), which deals with the higher-level issues of medium availability, and a physical layer interface (PHY).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The MAC is typically linked to the PHY by a four-bit 25 MHz synchronous parallel interface known as a media-independent interface (MII), or by a two-bit 50 MHz variant called reduced media independent interface (RMII).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In rare cases, the MII may be an external connection, but it is usually a connection between ICs in a network adapter or even two sections within a single IC.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The specs are written based on the assumption that the interface between MAC and PHY will be an MII, but they do not require it.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet or Ethernet hubs may use the MII to connect to multiple PHYs for their different interfaces.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The MII fixes the theoretical maximum data bit rate for all versions of Fast Ethernet to 100 Mbit/s.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The information rate actually observed on real networks is less than the theoretical maximum, due to the necessary header and trailer (addressing and error-detection bits) on every Ethernet frame, and the required interpacket gap between transmissions.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Initially, several Fast Ethernet standards for twisted-pair cable were standardized, including: 100BASE-TX (100 Mbit/s over two-pair Cat5 or better cable), 100BASE-T4 (100 Mbit/s over four-pair Cat3 or better cable, defunct), 100BASE-T2 (100 Mbit/s over two-pair Cat3 or better cable, also defunct).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The segment length for Ethernet over a twisted-pair link is limited to 100 metres (328 ft), the same limit as 10BASE-T and gigabit Ethernet.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] All initial standards were approved under IEEE 802.3 in 1995.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Of those, 100BASE-TX became extremely popular, supplanting the others.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Like 10BASE-T, the active pairs in a standard connection are terminated on pins 1, 2, 3 and 6.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Since a typical Category 5 cable contains four pairs and the performance requirements of 100BASE-TX do not exceed the capabilities of even the worst-performing pair, one typical cable can carry two 100BASE-TX links with a simple wiring adaptor on each end.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Cabling is conventionally wired to one of ANSI/TIA-568's termination standards, T568A or T568B.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-TX uses pairs 2 and 3 (orange and green).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The configuration of 100BASE-TX networks is very similar to 10BASE-T.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] When used to build a local area network, the devices on the network (computers, printers, etc.) are typically connected to a hub or switch, creating a star network.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Alternatively, it is possible to connect two devices directly using a crossover cable.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] With today's equipment, crossover cables are generally not needed as most equipment supports auto-negotiation along with auto MDI-X to select and match speed, duplex and pairing.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] With 100BASE-TX hardware, the raw bits, presented 4 bits wide clocked at 25 MHz at the MII, go through 4B5B binary encoding to generate a series of 0 and 1 symbols clocked at a 125 MHz symbol rate.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The 4B5B encoding provides DC equalization and spectrum shaping.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Just as in the 100BASE-FX case, the bits are then transferred to the physical medium attachment layer using NRZI encoding.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] However, 100BASE-TX introduces an additional, medium-dependent sublayer, which employs MLT-3 as a final encoding of the data stream before transmission, resulting in a maximum fundamental frequency of 31.25 MHz.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The procedure is borrowed from the ANSI X3.263 FDDI specifications, with minor changes.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In **100BASE-T1**, the data is transmitted over a single copper pair, 3 bits per symbol, each transmitted as a code pair using PAM3.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The twisted-pair cable is required to support 66 MHz, with a maximum length of 15 m.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The standard is intended for automotive applications or when Fast Ethernet is to be integrated into another application.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It was developed as Open Alliance BroadR-Reach (OABR) before IEEE standardization.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In **100BASE-T2**, standardized in IEEE 802.3y, the data is transmitted over two copper pairs, but these pairs are only required to be Category 3 (voice grade) rather than the Category 5 required by 100BASE-TX.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Data is transmitted and received on both pairs simultaneously, thus allowing full-duplex operation.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The 4-bit symbol is expanded into two 3-bit symbols through a non-trivial scrambling procedure based on a linear-feedback shift register.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] This is needed to flatten the bandwidth and emission spectrum of the signal, as well as to match transmission line properties.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The mapping of the original bits to the symbol codes is not constant in time and has a fairly large period (appearing as a pseudo-random sequence).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The final mapping from symbols to PAM-5 line modulation levels obeys the table on the right.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-T2 was not widely adopted, but the technology developed for it is used in 1000BASE-T.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] A very unusual 8B6T code was used to convert 8 data bits into 6 base-3 digits (the signal shaping is possible as there are nearly three times as many 6-digit base-3 numbers as there are 8-digit base-2 numbers).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The two resulting 3-digit base-3 symbols were sent in parallel over three pairs using 3-level pulse-amplitude modulation (PAM-3).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-T4 was not widely adopted but some of the technology developed for it is used in 1000BASE-T.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Very few hubs were released with 100BASE-T4 support.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Some examples include the 3com 3C250-T4 Superstack II HUB 100, IBM 8225 Fast Ethernet Stackable Hub and Intel LinkBuilder FMS 100 T4.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The same applies to network interface controllers.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Bridging 100BASE-T4 with 100BASE-TX required additional network equipment.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Proposed and marketed by Hewlett-Packard, 100BaseVG was an alternative design using category 3 cabling and a token concept instead of CSMA/CD.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It was slated for standardization as IEEE 802.12, but it quickly vanished when switched 100BASE-TX became popular.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] VG was similar to T4 in that it used more cable pairs combined with a lower carrier frequency to allow it to reach 100 Mbit/s on voice-grade cables.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It differed in the way those cables were assigned.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Whereas T4 would use the two extra pairs in different directions depending on the direction of data exchange, VG instead used two transmission modes.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In one, *control*, two pairs are used for transmission and reception as in classic Ethernet, while the other two pairs are used for flow control.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] In the second mode, *transmission*, all four are used to transfer data in a single direction.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The hubs implemented a token passing scheme to choose which of the attached nodes were allowed to communicate at any given time, based on signals sent to it from the nodes using control mode.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] When one node was selected to become active, it would switch to transfer mode, send or receive a packet, and return to control mode.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] This concept was intended to solve two problems.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The first was that it eliminated the need for collision detection and thereby reduced contention on busy networks.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] While any particular node may find itself throttled due to heavy traffic, the network as a whole would not end up losing efficiency due to collisions and the resulting rebroadcasts.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Under heavy use, the total throughput was increased compared to the other standards.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The other was that the hubs could examine the payload types and schedule the nodes based on their bandwidth requirements.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] For instance, a node sending a video signal may not require much bandwidth, but will require it to be predictable in terms of when it is delivered.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] A VG hub could schedule access on that node to ensure it received the transmission timeslots it needed while opening up the network at all other times to the other nodes.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] This style of access was known as demand priority.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fiber variants use fiber-optic cable with the listed interface types.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Interfaces may be fixed or modular, often as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP).
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] specification largely derived from FDDI.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] optics sharable with 10BASE-FL, thus making it possible to have an auto-negotiation scheme and use 10/100 fiber adapters.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] optical multiplexer used to split TX and RX signals into different wavelengths.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Fast Ethernet speed is not available on all SFP ports, but supported by some devices.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] An SFP port for Gigabit Ethernet should not be assumed to be backwards compatible with Fast Ethernet.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-X Ethernet is not backward compatible with 10BASE-F and is not forward compatible with 1000BASE-X.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-FX is a version of Fast Ethernet over optical fiber.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The 100BASE-FX physical medium dependent (PMD) sublayer is defined by FDDI's PMD, so 100BASE-FX is not compatible with 10BASE-FL, the 10 Mbit/s version over optical fiber.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-FX is still used for existing installations of multimode fiber where more speed is not required, like industrial automation plants.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-LFX is a non-standard term to refer to Fast Ethernet transmission.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It is very similar to 100BASE-FX but achieves longer distances up to 4–5 km over a pair of multi-mode fibers through the use of Fabry–Pérot laser transmitter running on 1310 nm wavelength.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] The signal attenuation per km at 1300 nm is about half the loss of 850 nm.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-SX is a version of Fast Ethernet over optical fiber standardized in TIA/EIA-785-1-2002.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It is a lower-cost, shorter-distance alternative to 100BASE-FX.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Because of the shorter wavelength used (850 nm) and the shorter distance supported (up to 300 m), 100BASE-SX may use less expensive optical components.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Because it uses the same wavelength as 10BASE-FL, the 10 Mbit/s version of Ethernet over optical fiber, 100BASE-SX can be backward-compatible with 10BASE-FL.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Cost and compatibility make 100BASE-SX an option for those upgrading from 10BASE-FL and who do not require longer distances.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-LX10 is a version of Fast Ethernet over optical fiber standardized in 802.3ah-2004 clause 58.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It has a 10 km reach over a pair of single-mode fibers.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-BX10 is a version of Fast Ethernet over optical fiber standardized in 802.3ah-2004 clause 58.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It uses an optical multiplexer to split TX and RX signals into different wavelengths on the same fiber.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It has a 10 km reach over a single strand of single-mode fiber.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-EX is very similar to 100BASE-LX10 but achieves longer distances up to 40 km over a pair of single-mode fibers due to higher quality optics than a LX10, running on 1310 nm wavelength lasers.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-EX is not a formal standard but an industry-accepted term.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] It is sometimes referred to as 100BASE-LH (long haul), and is easily confused with 100BASE-LX10 or 100BASE-ZX because the use of -LX(10), -LH, -EX, and -ZX is ambiguous between vendors.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] 100BASE-ZX is a non-standard but multi-vendor term to refer to Fast Ethernet transmission using 1,550 nm wavelength to achieve distances of at least 70 km over single-mode fiber.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Some vendors specify distances up to 160 km over single-mode fiber, sometimes called 100BASE-EZX.
[src:hdmi/100base-tx] Ranges beyond 80 km are highly dependent upon the path loss of the fiber in use, specifically the attenuation figure in dB per km, the number and quality of connectors/patch panels and splices located between transceivers.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:hdmi/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:hdmi/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:hdmi/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:hdmi/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:hdmi/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:hdmi/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:hdmi/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:hdmi/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:hdmi/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:hdmi/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:hdmi/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:hdmi/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:hdmi/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:hdmi/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:hdmi/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:hdmi/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:hdmi/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:hdmi/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:hdmi/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:hdmi/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:hdmi/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:hdmi/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:hdmi/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:hdmi/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:hdmi/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:hdmi/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:hdmi/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:hdmi/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:hdmi/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:hdmi/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:hdmi/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:hdmi/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:hdmi/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:hdmi/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:hdmi/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:hdmi/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:hdmi/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:hdmi/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:hdmi/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:hdmi/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:hdmi/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:hdmi/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:hdmi/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:hdmi/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:hdmi/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:hdmi/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:hdmi/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:hdmi/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:hdmi/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:hdmi/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:hdmi/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:hdmi/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:hdmi/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:hdmi/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:hdmi/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:hdmi/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:hdmi/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:hdmi/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] On June 5, 2015, Chinese manufacturer BOE showed a 10K display with an aspect ratio of 64:27 (≈21:9) and a resolution of 10240 × 4320.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] In November 2016, the Consumer Technology Association published CTA-861-G, an update to their standard for digital video transmission formats.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] This revision added support for 10240 × 4320, a 10K resolution with an aspect ratio of 64:27 (≈21:9), at up to 120 Hz.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] On January 4, 2017, HDMI version 2.1 was officially announced, and was later released on November 28, 2017.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] HDMI 2.1 includes support for all the formats listed in the CTA-861-G standard, including 10K (10240 × 4320) at up to 120 Hz.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] HDMI 2.1 specifies a new Ultra High Speed HDMI cable which supports a bandwidth of up to 48 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] Display Stream Compression (DSC) 1.2a is used for video formats higher than 8K resolution with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] 10K resolutions are also sometimes seen in the case of gaming, for instance high resolution screenshots in the case of Minecraft with the OptiFine mod.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] As of 2021, there are multiple companies producing photo cameras capable of 10K and higher resolutions, such as Phase One, Fujifilm, Hasselblad, and Sony.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] Other companies also create sensors capable of 10K resolution, though they are mostly not available to the general public, and are often used for scientific or industrial purposes.
[src:hdmi/10k-resolution] Blackmagic Design is the only company producing a video camera capable of filming in resolutions 10K or higher with their URSA Mini Pro 12K, and URSA Cine 12K & 17K.
[src:hdmi/1440p] 1440p video mastered from 4:3 ratio content can be displayed with 1920×1440 or higher resolution such as QXGA or 2304×1440 with scaling, windowboxing, or pillarboxing.
[src:hdmi/1440p] Widescreen 16:9 aspect ratio 1440p requires 2560×1440 (WQHD) resolution, possible with WQXGA, 2560×1920, or higher resolution with letterboxing, scaling, or windowboxing.
[src:hdmi/1440p] The HDMI 1.3 specification supports WQXGA, and hence widescreen 1440p.
[src:hdmi/1440p] Early 1440p computer displays became commonly available in 2010.
[src:hdmi/1440p] Dell's UltraSharp U2711 monitor was released in 2010 as WQHD, with a 1440p widescreen.
[src:hdmi/1440p] The 27-inch Apple LED Cinema Display released in 2010 also had a native resolution of 2560 × 1440, as did the Apple Thunderbolt Display which was sold from July 2011 to June 2016.
[src:hdmi/1440p] MacBook with Retina Display (2012) is also one of the earliest laptops that utilise 1440p widescreen.
[src:hdmi/1440p] By 2020, 1440p had expanded to a common resolution for computer gaming, with multiple video cards available that supported high frame rates at that resolution.
[src:hdmi/1440p] In early 2021, QHD gaming laptops with fast refresh rates were introduced by multiple computer manufacturers.
[src:hdmi/1440p] According to Steam's July 2024 Hardware & Software Survey, the resolution 2560 x 1440 has increased in overall usage on Steam by ~0.7% from May 2024, totaling to ~20% of its total userbase.
[src:hdmi/1440p] In relation to smartphones, 1440p displays are sometimes marketed as "Quad HD", as it is four times the resolution of 720p high definition.
[src:hdmi/1440p] The Vivo Xplay 3S, released December 2013, was the first smartphone to use a 1440p display; by 2015, 1440p had seen wider adoption by high-end flagship smartphones from major companies.
[src:hdmi/1440p] An example of a smartphone with a 1440p display is the 1st generation Google Pixel XL.
[src:hdmi/1440p] In September 2020, Microsoft revealed the Xbox Series S would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS.
[src:hdmi/1440p] In July 2022, Sony added 1440p support for the PlayStation 5.
[src:hdmi/1440p] In April 2025, Nintendo revealed the Nintendo Switch 2 would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS output via HDMI when playing in TV mode.
[src:hdmi/1440p] The label "2K" is sometimes used to refer to 2560 × 1440 (commonly known as 1440p).
[src:hdmi/1440p] This is inconsistent with "4K" denoting approximately 4,000 horizontal pixels, which makes 1920 or 2048 pixels wide the closest to "2K", a label which predates the use of 2560 × 1440.
[src:hdmi/1440p] Some sources and manufacturers prefer "2.5K" as a term for 2560 × 1440 to avoid this confusion, and there is a similar "2.7K" (2720 × 1530) used by some drones, as well as a "2.8K" (2880 × 1620).
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] As of May 2025, 16K resolutions can be run in prototype displays, large public displays or using multi-monitor setups with AMD Eyefinity, or Nvidia Surround or Mosaic Technology.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] In early 2014, Japanese companies Nest+Visual, Sony and Indy Associates produced the first 16K film, using a Sony F65 CineAlta camera equipped with an anamorphic lens.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] The film was presented in March 2014 on a multi-screen video display at the Tokyo International Airport in Haneda, Japan.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] In 2016, AMD announced a target for their future graphics cards to support 16K resolution with a refresh rate of 240 Hz for "true immersion" in VR.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Linus Tech Tips released a series of videos in 2017 attempting to play video games at 16K using sixteen 4K monitors.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] In 2018, US filmmaker Martin Lisius released a short time-lapse film titled, "Prairie Wind" that he produced using a 2-camera Canon EOS 5DS system he developed.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Two still images were stitched together to create one 15985 × 5792 pixel image and then rendered as 16K resolution video with an extremely wide aspect ratio of 2.76∶1.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] This is among the first known 16K videos to exist.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Innolux displayed the world's first 100-inch 16K (15360 × 8640) display module at Touch Taiwan in August 2018.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Sony introduced a 64 by 18 foot (19.5 m × 5.5 m) commercial 16K display at NAB 2019 that is set to be released in Japan.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] It is made up of 576 modules (each 360 × 360) in a formation of 48 by 12 modules, forming a 17280 × 4320 screen with a 4∶1 aspect ratio.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] On June 26, 2019, VESA formally released the DisplayPort 2.0 standard with support for one 16K (15360 × 8640-pixel) display supporting 30-bit-per-pixel 4:4:4 RGB/Y′CBCR-color HDR video at a refresh rate of 60 Hz using DSC video compression.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Sphere, an entertainment venue located in Las Vegas, Nevada, opened with a wraparound interior LED screen on September 29, 2023.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] According to Sphere Entertainment, the screen within the theater is 160,000 sq ft (15,000 m2) and supports a 16K (16000 × 16000-pixel) resolution, making it the highest resolution LED screen in the world.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] At "Display Week" 2023, Chinese manufacturer BOE unveiled the world's first 110-inch 16K consumer television.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] The LCD-based screen outputs a native resolution of 15360×8640 pixels, which is four times the pixel count of 8K and sixteen times that of 4K.
[src:hdmi/16k-resolution] Operating at a 60 Hz refresh rate, the television delivers a brightness of 400 nits and a contrast ratio of 1200:1.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] For 90 years, 20th Century has been one of the major American film studios.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It was founded on May 31, 1935, by the merger of Fox Film Corporation and Twentieth Century Pictures, and was one of the original "Big Five" among eight majors of Hollywood's Golden Age.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1985, it was acquired by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, which was renamed 21st Century Fox in 2013 after it spun off its publishing assets.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Disney purchased most of 21st Century Fox's assets, which included 20th Century Fox, on March 20, 2019.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The studio adopted its current name on January 17, 2020, in order to avoid confusion with Fox Corporation, and subsequently started to use it for the copyright of 20th Century and Searchlight Pictures productions on December 4.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century is currently one of five live-action film studios within the Walt Disney Studios, alongside Walt Disney Pictures, Marvel Studios, Lucasfilm, and its sister speciality unit, Searchlight Pictures.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century also releases animated films produced by its animation division, 20th Century Animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century Pictures' Joseph Schenck and Darryl F.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck left United Artists over a stock dispute, and began merger talks with the management of financially struggling Fox Film, under President Sidney Kent.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Spyros Skouras, then manager of the Fox West Coast Theaters, helped make it happen (and later became president of the new company).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The company had been struggling since founder William Fox lost control of the company in 1930.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Film Corporation and Twentieth Century Pictures merged in 1935.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Initially, it was speculated in *The New York Times* that the newly merged company would be named "Fox-Twentieth Century".
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The new company, Twentieth Century-Fox Film Corporation, began trading on May 31, 1935.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Kent remained at the company, joining Schenck and Zanuck.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck replaced Winfield Sheehan as the company's production chief.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The company established a special training school.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Lynn Bari, Patricia Farr and Anne Nagel were among 14 young women "launched on the trail of film stardom" on August 6, 1935, when they each received a six-month contract with Twentieth Century-Fox after spending 18 months in the school.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The contracts included a studio option for renewal for as long as seven years.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] For many years, Twentieth Century-Fox identified themselves as having been founded in 1915, the year Fox Film was founded.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] For instance, it marked 1945 as its 30th anniversary.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] However, it has considered the 1935 merger as its founding in recent years, even though most film historians agree it was founded in 1915.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The company's films retained the Twentieth Century Pictures searchlight logo on their opening credits as well as its opening fanfare, but with the name changed to Twentieth Century-Fox.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After the merger was completed, Zanuck signed young actors to help carry Twentieth Century-Fox: Tyrone Power, Linda Darnell, Carmen Miranda, Don Ameche, Henry Fonda, Gene Tierney, Sonja Henie, and Betty Grable.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also hired Alice Faye and Shirley Temple, who appeared in several major films for the studio in the 1930s.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Higher attendance during World War II helped Twentieth Century-Fox overtake RKO and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer to become the third most profitable film studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1941, Zanuck was commissioned as a lieutenant colonel in the U.S.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Signal Corps and assigned to supervise the production of U.S.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] His partner, William Goetz, filled in at Twentieth Century-Fox.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1942, Spyros Skouras succeeded Kent as president of the studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] During the next few years, with pictures like *Wilson* (1944), *The Razor's Edge* (1946), *Boomerang*, *Gentleman's Agreement* (both 1947), *The Snake Pit* (1948), and *Pinky* (1949), Zanuck established a reputation for provocative, adult films.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also specialized in adaptations of best-selling books such as Ben Ames Williams' *Leave Her to Heaven* (1945), starring Gene Tierney, which was the highest-grossing Twentieth Century-Fox film of the 1940s.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The studio also produced film versions of Broadway musicals, including the Rodgers and Hammerstein films, beginning with the musical version of *State Fair* (1945), the only work that the partnership wrote specially for films.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After the war, audiences slowly drifted away.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox held on to its theaters until a court-mandated "divorce"; they were spun off as Fox National Theaters in 1953.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] That year, with attendance at half the 1946 level, Twentieth Century-Fox gambled on an unproven process.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] President Spyros Skouras struck a deal with the inventor Henri Chrétien, leaving the other film studios empty-handed, and in 1953 introduced CinemaScope in the studio's groundbreaking feature film *The Robe*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck announced in February 1953 that henceforth all Twentieth Century-Fox pictures would be made in CinemaScope.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] To convince theater owners to install this new process, Twentieth Century-Fox agreed to help pay conversion costs (about $25,000 per screen); and to ensure enough product, Twentieth Century-Fox leased access to CinemaScope to any rival studio choosing to use it.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Seeing the box-office for the first two CinemaScope features, *The Robe* and *How to Marry a Millionaire* (also 1953), Warner Bros., MGM, RKO, Universal-International, Columbia, UA, Allied Artists, and Disney quickly adopted the process.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1956, Twentieth Century-Fox engaged Robert Lippert to establish a subsidiary company, Regal Pictures, later Associated Producers Incorporated to film B pictures in CinemaScope (but "branded" RegalScope).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox produced new musicals using the CinemaScope process including *Carousel* and *The King and I* (both 1956).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] CinemaScope brought a brief upturn in attendance, but by 1956 the numbers again began to slide.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] That year Darryl Zanuck announced his resignation as head of production.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck moved to Paris, setting up as an independent producer, seldom being in the United States for many years.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In mid 1956, the company loaned the pre-1948 film library, including TV distribution rights, but not the copyrights of these films, to National Telefilm Associates for 10 years.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck's successor, producer Buddy Adler, died a year later.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] President Spyros Skouras brought in a series of production executives, but none had Zanuck's success.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] By the early 1960s, Twentieth Century-Fox was in trouble.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] A new version of *Cleopatra* (1963) began production in 1959 with Joan Collins in the lead.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] As a publicity gimmick, producer Walter Wanger offered $1 million to Elizabeth Taylor if she would star; she accepted and costs for *Cleopatra* began to escalate.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Richard Burton's on-set romance with Taylor was surrounding the media.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] However, Skouras' selfish preferences and inexperienced micromanagement on the film's production did nothing to speed up production on *Cleopatra*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Meanwhile, another remake—of the Cary Grant hit *My Favorite Wife* (1940)—was rushed into production in an attempt to turn over a quick profit to help keep Twentieth Century-Fox afloat.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The romantic comedy entitled *Something's Got to Give* paired Marilyn Monroe, Twentieth Century-Fox's most bankable star of the 1950s, with Dean Martin and director George Cukor.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The troubled Monroe caused delays daily, and it quickly descended into a costly debacle.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] As *Cleopatra*'s budget passed $10 million, eventually costing around $40 million, Twentieth Century-Fox sold its back lot (now the site of Century City) to Alcoa in 1961 to raise funds.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After several weeks of script rewrites on the Monroe picture and very little progress, mostly due to director George Cukor's filming methods, in addition to Monroe's chronic sinusitis, Monroe was fired from *Something's Got to Give* and two months later she was found dead.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] According to Twentieth Century-Fox files, she was rehired within weeks for a two-picture deal totaling $1 million, $500,000 to finish *Something's Got to Give* (plus a bonus at completion), and another $500,000 for *What a Way to Go*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Elizabeth Taylor's disruptive reign on the *Cleopatra* set continued unchallenged from 1960 into 1962, though three Twentieth Century-Fox executives went to Rome in June 1962 to fire her.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Mankiewicz had filmed out of sequence and had only done interiors, so Twentieth Century-Fox was then forced to allow Taylor several more weeks of filming.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In the meantime during that summer of 1962 Fox released nearly all of its contract stars to offset burgeoning costs, including Jayne Mansfield.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] With few pictures on the schedule, Skouras wanted to rush Zanuck's big-budget war epic *The Longest Day* (1962), an accurate account of the Allied invasion of Normandy on June 6, 1944, with a huge international cast, into release as another source of quick cash.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] This offended Zanuck, still Twentieth Century-Fox's largest shareholder, for whom *The Longest Day* was a labor of love that he had dearly wanted to produce for many years.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After it became clear that *Something's Got to Give* would not be able to progress without Monroe in the lead (Martin had refused to work with anyone else), Skouras finally decided that re-signing her was unavoidable.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] But days before filming was due to resume, she was found dead at her Los Angeles home and the picture resumed filming as *Move Over, Darling*, with Doris Day and James Garner in the leads.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The unfinished scenes from *Something's Got to Give* were shelved for nearly 40 years.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Rather than being rushed into release as if it were a B-picture, *The Longest Day* was lovingly and carefully produced under Zanuck's supervision.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It was finally released at a length of three hours and was well received.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] At the next board meeting, Zanuck spoke for eight hours, convincing directors that Skouras was mismanaging the company and that he was the only possible successor.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck was installed as chairman, and then named his son Richard Zanuck as president.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also had two big science-fiction hits in the decade: *Fantastic Voyage* (1966), and the original *Planet of the Apes* (1968), starring Charlton Heston, Kim Hunter, and Roddy McDowall.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] *Fantastic Voyage* was the last film made in CinemaScope; the studio had held on to the format while Panavision lenses were being used elsewhere.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Zanuck stayed on as chairman until 1971, but there were several expensive flops in his last years, resulting in Twentieth Century-Fox posting losses from 1969 to 1971.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Following his removal and replacement by Dennis Stanfill as chairman, and after an uncertain period, new management brought Twentieth Century-Fox back to health.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Stulberg and production head Alan Ladd, Jr., Twentieth Century-Fox films connected with modern audiences.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Board chairman Dennis Stanfill used the profits to acquire resort properties, soft-drink bottlers, Australian theaters and other properties in an attempt to diversify enough to offset the boom-or-bust cycle of picture-making.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Foreshadowing a pattern of film production still yet to come, in late 1973 Twentieth Century-Fox partnered with Warner Bros. to co-produce *The Towering Inferno* (1974), an all-star action blockbuster from producer Irwin Allen.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Both studios found themselves owning the rights to books about burning skyscrapers.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Allen insisted on a meeting with the heads of both studios and announced that as Twentieth Century-Fox was already in the lead with their property it would be career suicide to have competing movies.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Thus the first joint-venture studio deal was struck.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In hindsight, while it may be commonplace now, back in the 1970s, it was a risky, but revolutionary, idea that paid off handsomely at both domestic and international box offices around the world.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox's success reached new heights by backing the most profitable film made up to that time, *Star Wars* (1977).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Substantial financial gains were realized as a result of the film's unprecedented success: from a low of $6 in June 1976, stock prices more than quadrupled to almost $27 after *Star Wars* release; 1976 revenues of $195 million rose to $301 million in 1977.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] With financial stability came new owners, when 20th Century-Fox was sold for $720 million on June 8, 1981, to investors Marc Rich and Marvin Davis.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century-Fox's assets included Pebble Beach Golf Links, the Aspen Skiing Company and a Century City property upon which Davis built and twice sold Fox Plaza.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] By 1984, Rich had become a fugitive from justice, having fled to Switzerland after being charged by U.S. federal prosecutors with tax evasion, racketeering and illegal trading with Iran during the Iran hostage crisis.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Rich's assets were frozen by U.S. authorities.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1984, Marvin Davis bought out Marc Rich's 50% interest in 20th Century-Fox Film Corporation for an undisclosed amount, reported to be $116 million.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Davis sold this interest to Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation for $250 million in March 1985.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Davis later backed out of a deal with Murdoch to purchase John Kluge's Metromedia television stations.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Murdoch went ahead alone and bought the stations, and later bought out Davis' remaining stake in Twentieth Century-Fox for $325 million.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] From 1985, the hyphen was permanently deleted from the brand name, with *Twentieth Century-Fox* changing to *Twentieth Century Fox*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] To gain FCC approval of 20th Century-Fox's purchase of Metromedia's television holdings, once the stations of the long-dissolved DuMont network, Murdoch had to become a U.S. citizen.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] He did so in 1985, and in 1986 the new Fox Broadcasting Company took to the air.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Over the next 20-odd years the network and owned-stations group expanded to become extremely profitable for News Corporation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Then in 1993, 20th Century Fox bought the superhero rights to the X-Men, while the Fantastic Four was bought in 1998.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Then Bryan Singer directed the first film and the second film, while Brett Ratner was hired to direct the third film of the original trilogy.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1994, 20th Century Fox would establish four new divisions: Fox Searchlight Pictures, Fox Family Films, Fox Animation Studios, and Fox 2000 Pictures.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Searchlight would specialize in the specialty and indie film market, with Thomas Rothman, then president of production at The Samuel Goldwyn Company, being brought on to head up the new studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It was soon given its name with Rothman as its founding president.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Family Films was tasked with producing films geared towards families, under John Matoian.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Animation Studios was established on August 9, 1994, designed to compete with Walt Disney Feature Animation, whom had found success in the Disney Renaissance.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Don Bluth and Gary Goldman of the failing Sullivan Bluth Studios were appointed to head the new $100 million animation studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox 2000 Pictures was formed to specialize in mid-budget-ranging films targeted towards underserved groups of audiences, with Laura Ziskin brought on as president.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In November 1995, 20th Century Fox entered a $50 million agreement to purchase the library of bankrupt Carolco Pictures, which would have given Fox the rights to make a sequel based on the hit Carolco film *Terminator 2: Judgement Day*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] However, Fox dropped their bid in January 1996, after French company Canal+ submitted a $58 million counterbid for the assets.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In August 1997, Fox's Los Angeles-based visual effects company, VIFX, acquired majority interest in Blue Sky Studios to form a new visual effects and animation company, temporarily renamed "Blue Sky/VIFX".
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Blue Sky had previously did the character animation of MTV Films' first film *Joe's Apartment.*Following the studio's expansion, Blue Sky produced character animation for the films *Alien Resurrection*, *A Simple Wish*, *Mouse Hunt*, *Star Trek: Insurrection* and *Fight Club*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] VIFX was later sold to another VFX studio Rhythm and Hues Studios in March 1999.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] According to Blue Sky founder Chris Wedge, Fox considered selling Blue Sky as well by 2000 due to financial difficulties in the visual effects industry in general.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In February 1998, following the success of Fox Animation Studios' first film *Anastasia*, Fox Family Films changed its name to Fox Animation Studios and dropped its live action production. which would be picked up by other production units.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The actual Fox Animation Studios would become a division of the formerly-named Fox Family Films, being referred to as the Phoenix studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] However, Fox Animation Studios in Los Angeles would be renamed to 20th Century Fox Animation between 1998 and 1999.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The Phoenix studio would face financial problems, eventually with Fox laying off 300 of the nearly 380 people who worked at the Phoenix studio to "make films more efficiently".
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After the box-office failure of *Titan A.E.*, Fox Animation Studios would shut down on June 26, 2000.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Their last film set to be made would have been an adaptation of Wayne Barlowe's illustrated novel *Barlowe's Inferno*, and was set to be done entirely with computer animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Another film they would have made was *The Little Beauty King*, an adult animated film directed by Steve Oedekerk, which would have been a satire of the films from the Disney Renaissance.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Chris Wedge, film producer Lori Forte, and Fox Animation executive Chris Meledandri presented Fox with a script for a comedy feature film titled *Ice Age*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Studio management pressured staff to sell their remaining shares and options to Fox on the promise of continued employment on feature-length films.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The studio moved to White Plains, New York and started production on *Ice Age*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] As the film wrapped, Fox, having little faith in the film, feared that it might bomb at the box office.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox terminated half of the production staff and tried unsuccessfully to find a buyer for the film and the studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Instead, *Ice Age* was released by Fox in conjunction with Twentieth Century Fox Animation on March 15, 2002, to critical and commercial success, receiving a nomination for an Academy Award for Best Animated Feature at the 75th Academy Awards in 2003.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] *Ice Age* would spawn a franchise and bolster Blue Sky into producing feature films and becoming a household name in feature animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] From 2000 to 2010, 20th Century Fox was the international distributor for MGM/UA releases.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In the 1980s, 20th Century Fox – through a joint venture with CBS called CBS/Fox Video – had distributed certain UA films on video; thus UA has come full circle by switching to 20th Century Fox for video distribution.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century Fox also makes money distributing films for small independent film companies.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 2006, 20th Century Fox terminated its production with Bad Hat Harry Productions for five years, because Bryan Singer left *X-Men: The Last Stand* to direct *Superman Returns* (2006) for Warner Bros.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Pictures, then he returned to produce the first film and direct its sequel in the prequel trilogy, starting in 2011.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In late 2006, Fox Atomic was started up under Fox Searchlight head Peter Rice and COO John Hegeman as a sibling production division under Fox Filmed Entertainment.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In early 2008, Atomic's marketing unit was transferred to Fox Searchlight and 20th Century Fox, when Hegeman moved to New Regency Productions.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After two middling successes and falling short with other films, the unit was shut down in April 2009.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The remaining films under its Atomic label in production and post-productions were transferred to 20th Century Fox and Fox Searchlight with Liebling overseeing them.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 2008, 20th Century Fox announced an Asian subsidiary, Fox STAR Studios, a joint venture with STAR TV, also owned by News Corporation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It was reported that Fox STAR would start by producing films for the Bollywood market, then expand to several Asian markets.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In the same year, Twentieth Century Fox started Fox International Productions, but the division was closed in 2017.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Chernin Entertainment was founded by Peter Chernin after he stepped down as president of 20th Century Fox's then-parent company News Corporation in 2009.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Chernin Entertainment's five-year first-look deal for the film and television was signed with 20th Century Fox and 20th Century Fox Television in 2009.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On June 28, 2012, Rupert Murdoch announced that News Corporation would be split into two publishing and media-oriented companies: a new News Corporation and 21st Century Fox, which operated the Fox Entertainment Group and 20th Century Fox.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Murdoch considered the name of the new company a way to maintain the 20th Century Fox heritage.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On August 20, 2012, 20th Century Fox entered a five-year distribution agreement with DreamWorks Animation, which began in 2013, after their distribution deal with Paramount Pictures ended with the 2012 release of *Rise of the Guardians*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] DreamWorks Animation's first film to be distributed under the new agreement was *The Croods*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Stage Productions was formed in June 2013.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In August, the same year, 20th Century Fox started a theatrical joint venture with a trio of producers, both film and theater, Kevin McCollum, John Davis and Tom McGrath.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On September 20, 2017, Locksmith Animation formed a multi-year production deal with 20th Century Fox, who would distribute Locksmith's films under 20th Century Fox Animation, with Locksmith aiming to release a film every 12–18 months.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The first film to be released under the production company was *Ron's Gone Wrong*, which was released on October 22, 2021, by 20th Century Studios and was the only film to be released by the studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Technoprops, a VFX company that worked on *Avatar* and *The Jungle Book*, was purchased in April 2017 to operate as Fox VFX Lab.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Technoprops' founder Glenn Derry would continue to run the company as vice president of visual effect reporting to Gerard Bevan and John Kilkenny, VFX president.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On October 30, 2017, Vanessa Morrison was named president of a newly created 20th Century Fox division, Fox Family, reporting to the chairman & CEO and Vice Chairman of 20th Century Fox.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The family division would develop films that appeal to younger moviegoers and their parents both animated films and films with live-action elements.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Also, the division would oversee the studio's family animated television business, which produces holiday television specials based on existing film properties, and oversee feature film adaptation of its TV shows.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] To replace Morrison at Fox Animation, Andrea Miloro and Robert Baird were named co-presidents of 20th Century Fox Animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century Fox issued a default notice in regards to its licensing agreement for the under-construction 20th Century Fox World theme park in Malaysia by Genting Malaysia Bhd.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In November 2018 Genting Malaysia filed suit in response and included soon to be parent the Walt Disney Company.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On December 14, 2017, Disney announced plans to purchase most of 21st Century Fox, including 20th Century Fox, for $52.4 billion.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After a bid from Comcast (owner of NBCUniversal) for $65 billion, Disney counterbid with $71.3 billion.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On July 19, 2018, Comcast dropped out of the bid for 21st Century Fox in favor of Sky plc and Sky UK.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Eight days later, Disney and 21st Century Fox shareholders approved the merger between the two companies.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Various units were moved out from under 20th Century Fox at acquisition in months after the merger along with several rounds of layoffs.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The Fox Research Library was folded into the Walt Disney Archives and Walt Disney Imagineering Archives in January 2020.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The last film to use the "20th Century Fox" name was *Underwater*, which was released on January 10, 2020.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After the box office failures of films like *Dark Phoenix* and *Stuber*, Disney halted development on several projects, though films such as *Free Guy* and the *Avatar* sequels managed to continue production.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox's slate would be reduced to 10 films per year, half of them being made for the Hulu and then-upcoming Disney+ streaming services.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Projects from 20th Century Fox franchises such as *Home Alone*, *Cheaper by the Dozen*, *Night at the Museum*, *Diary of a Wimpy Kid*, and *Ice Age* were later announced for Disney+.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] These projects would later be fully revealed during Disney's Investor Day in December 2020 as feature films for the aforementioned streaming service.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The first of these projects was *Home Sweet Home Alone*, which was released on November 12, 2021.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On January 17, 2020, Disney renamed the studio to "20th Century Studios", which served to help avoid brand confusion with Fox Corporation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment distributes the films produced by 20th Century and Searchlight in home media under their respective labels.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The first film released by Disney under the studio's new name was *The Call of the Wild*, which was released on February 21, 2020.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Ferrari* (2019), among its four Academy Award nominations, earned the studio its first Best Picture nomination post-Disney acquisition.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In the same year, held-over production president Emma Watts left the company.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On March 12, 2020, Steve Asbell was named president, production of 20th Century Studios, while Morrison was named president, streaming, Walt Disney Studios Motion Picture Production to oversee live-action development and production of Walt Disney Pictures and 20th Century Studios for Disney+.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Philip Steuer will now lead physical and post-production and VFX, as president of production at Walt Disney Studios Motion Picture Production.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Randi Hiller will now lead casting as executive VP casting, overseeing both Walt Disney Pictures and 20th Century Studios.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Steuer has served as executive VP of physical production for Walt Disney Studios since 2015, and Hiller has led casting for Walt Disney Studios since 2011.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Both will dual-report to Asbell and Sean Bailey.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On February 9, 2021, Disney announced that Blue Sky Studios would shut down in April 2021, and that it would be succeeded by 20th Century Animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] A spokesperson for the company explained that in light of the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic's continued economic impact on all of its businesses, it was no longer sustainable for them to run a third feature animation studio.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In addition, production on a film adaptation of the webcomic *Nimona*, originally scheduled to be released on January 14, 2022, was cancelled as a result of its closure.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The studio's film library and intellectual properties are retained by Disney via 20th Century Animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Although Disney did not give an exact date as to when the studio would be closing down initially, former animator Rick Fournier confirmed on April 10 it was their last day of operation, three days after founder Chris Wedge released a farewell letter on social media.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] *Nimona* would be picked up by Annapurna Pictures in early 2022 for release on Netflix in 2023.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On November 22, 2021, Disney Media and Entertainment Distribution and WarnerMedia reached an agreement to allow select 20th Century Studios films be shared between Disney+, Hulu, and HBO Max through late 2022.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The new agreement negotiated by Gerard Devan and John Gelke is an amendment to the original agreement between 20th Century Fox and HBO that Disney inherited after its acquisition of Fox in 2019, and as such, is not expected to be renewed.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Following the end of the 20th Century-HBO deal, Disney planned to retain the 20th Century films on their own streaming platforms going forward after 2022.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The first film to this new strategy was *Ron's Gone Wrong*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Also in 2021, Disney had launched a video game based-studio 20th Century Games.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Similar to its predecessors—FoxNext, Fox Interactive and 20th Century Fox Games—it acts as a distributor and has partnered with other triple-A game studios.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Its first title was *Aliens: Fireteam Elite*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On February 8, 2022, Steven Spielberg's 2021 film version of *West Side Story*, among its seven Academy Award nominations, earned 20th Century Studios its first Best Picture nomination post-rebranding.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In March 2023, it was announced that Marvel Comics would be launching a 20th Century Studios imprint, which would release comics based on 20th Century franchises.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The first comic under the label would be a *Planet of the Apes* comic.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] On February 26, 2024, Walt Disney Pictures announced the immediate departure of its president, Sean Bailey, with Searchlight Pictures president David Greenbaum assuming his position.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Greenbaum would lead Walt Disney Pictures and co-lead 20th Century with Steve Asbell as president.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In April 2025, Disney announced that it would not renew its lease with Fox Corporation and that it would vacate the Fox Studio Lot in Century City at the end of 2025.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] As a result, 20th Century relocated to the Walt Disney Studios in Burbank.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Television is the television production division of 20th Century Studios.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It was known as 20th Century Fox Television until it adopted the 20th Television name in 2020.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The 20th Television name was already in use prior to 2020, as the original 20th Television was the studio's television syndication division until it was folded into Disney–ABC Domestic Television in 2020.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] During the mid-1950s, feature films were released to television in the hope that they would broaden sponsorship and help the distribution of network programs.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Blocks of one-hour programming of feature films to national sponsors on 128 stations were organized by 20th Century Fox and National Telefilm Associates.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] 20th Century Fox received 50% interest in the NTA Film Network after it sold its library to National Telefilm Associates.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] This gave 90 minutes of cleared time a week and syndicated feature films (under the package title "Premiere Performance") to 110 non-interconnected stations for sale to national sponsors.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox bought out the remaining assets of Four Star Television from Ronald Perelman's Compact Video in 1996.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The majority of Four Star Television's library of programs are controlled by 20th Television today.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] After Murdoch's numerous buyouts during the buyout era of the eighties, News Corporation had built up financial debts of $7 billion (much from Sky TV in the UK), despite the many assets that were held by NewsCorp.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The high levels of debt caused Murdoch to sell many of the American magazine interests he had acquired in the mid-1980s.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Between 1933 and 1937, a custom record label called *Fox Movietone* was produced starting at F-100 and running through F-136.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It featured songs from 20th Century Fox movies, first using material recorded and issued on Victor's Bluebird label and halfway through switched to material recorded and issued on ARC's dime store labels (Melotone, Perfect, etc.).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] These scarce records were sold only at Fox Theaters.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The music arm of 20th Century Fox, 20th Century-Fox Records, was founded in 1958.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Fox Records was the 20th Century Fox's music arm since 1992 before being renamed to Fox Music in 2000.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It encompasses music publishing and licensing businesses, dealing primarily with Fox Entertainment Group's television and film soundtracks under license by Universal Music Group, EMI, PolyGram, Bertelsmann Music Group, Sony Music, and Warner Music Group.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It would also go defunct on January 17, 2020, and was subsequently folded into Hollywood Records.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The **Newman Scoring Stage**, named after composer Alfred Newman, is a large scoring studio located on the Fox Studio Lot, spanning almost 700 square meters, and is one of the largest music recording spaces in the world.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] It is also equipped with a 96 Channel AMS Neve 88RS-SP mixing console.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The *Twentieth Century Fox Presents* radio series were broadcast between 1936 and 1942.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] More often than not, the shows were a radio preview featuring a medley of the songs and soundtracks from the latest movie being released into the theaters, much like the modern-day movie trailers we now see on TV, to encourage folks to head down to their nearest Picture House.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The radio shows featured the original stars, with the announcer narrating a lead-up that encapsulated the performance.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] From its earliest ventures into movie production, Fox Film Corporation operated its own processing laboratories.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] The original lab was located in Fort Lee, New Jersey along with the studios.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] A lab was included with the new studio built in Los Angeles in 1916.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Freedman, the Fort Lee lab was moved into the new Fox Studios building in Manhattan in 1919.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In 1932, Freedman bought the labs from Fox for $2,000,000 to bolster what at that time was a failing Fox liquidity.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] He renamed the operation "DeLuxe Laboratories," which much later became Deluxe Entertainment Services Group.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] In the 1940s Freedman sold the labs back to what was then 20th Century Fox and remained as president into the 1960s.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p01] Under Freedman's leadership, DeLuxe added two more labs in Chicago and Toronto and processed film from studios other than Fox, such as UA and Universal.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] The 20th Century Fox production logo and fanfare originated as the logo of Twentieth Century Pictures and was adopted by 20th Century-Fox after the merger in 1935.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] It consists of a stacked block-letter three-dimensional, monolithic logotype (nicknamed "the Monument") surrounded by Art deco buildings and illuminated by searchlights.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In the production logo that appears at the start of films, the searchlights are animated and the sequence is accompanied by a distinctive fanfare that was originally composed in 1933 by Alfred Newman.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] The original layout of the logo was designed by special effects animator and matte painting artist Emil Kosa Jr.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In 1953, Rocky Longo, an artist at Pacific Title, was hired to recreate the original logo design for the new CinemaScope picture process.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] Longo tilted the "0" in "20th" to have the logo maintain proportions in the wider CinemaScope format.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] Alfred Newman also composed an extended version of the logo's fanfare to be heard during the CinemaScope logo that would follow after the Fox logo.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] Although the format had since declined, director George Lucas specifically requested that the CinemaScope version of the fanfare be used for the opening titles of *Star Wars* (1977).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] Additionally, the film's main theme was composed by John Williams in the same key as the fanfare (B♭ major), serving as an extension to it of sorts.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In 1981, the logo was altered with the re-straightening of the "0" in "20th".
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] It would later be re-recorded by David Newman in 1997 and again in 1998.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In 2009, an updated logo created by Blue Sky Studios (a prototype version of the 2009 structure exists) debuted with the release of *Avatar*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In 2013, the News Corporation byline was removed.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] On January 17, 2020, it was reported that Disney had begun to phase out the "Fox" name from the studio's branding as it is no longer tied to the current Fox Corporation, with 20th Century Fox and Fox Searchlight Pictures respectively renamed to 20th Century Studios and Searchlight Pictures.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] Branding elements associated with the studio, including the searchlights, monolith, and fanfare, will remain in use.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] The first film that carries the new 20th Century Studios name is *The Call of the Wild* (coincidentally the original film adaptation was the original Twentieth Century Pictures' final movie before its merger with Fox Film).
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] For the 20th Century Studios logo, its print logo debuted on a movie poster of *The New Mutants* while the on-screen logo debuted in a television advertisement for and the full version debuted on February 21, 2020, with the film *The Call of the Wild*.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] In 2020, 20th Century Studios logo was animated by Picturemill (the prototype version of the 2020 structure and the 2021 structure with the 2009 sky background exists and appeared in some of Picturemill's reels), while MOCEAN animated Searchlight Pictures logo, based on Blue Sky Studios' animation.
[src:hdmi/20th-century-studios-p02] It features a different sky backdrop, the Los Angeles skyline is larger and more detailed, and the rest of the structure appears darker with more realistic lighting.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Introduced in 2003, HDMI largely replaced older analog video standards such as composite video, S-Video, and VGA in consumer electronics.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It was developed based on the CEA-861 standard, which was also used with the earlier Digital Visual Interface (DVI).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI is electrically compatible with DVI video signals, and adapters allow interoperability between the two without signal conversion or loss of quality.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Adapters and active converters are also available for connecting HDMI to other video interfaces, including the older analog formats, as well as digital formats such as DisplayPort.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI has gone through multiple revisions since its introduction, with each version adding new features while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It also supports the Display Data Channel (DDC), used for automatic configuration between source devices and displays.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Newer versions include advanced capabilities such as 3D video, higher resolutions, and expanded color spaces.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The Audio Return Channel (ARC) and Enhanced Audio Return Channel (eARC) allow audio to be sent from a display back to an audio system over the same HDMI cable.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Smaller connector types, Mini and Micro HDMI, were also introduced for use with compact devices like camcorders and tablets.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] As of January 2026, nearly 14 billion HDMI-enabled devices have been sold worldwide, making it one of the most widely adopted audio/video interfaces in consumer electronics.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI founders were Hitachi, Panasonic, Sanyo (as a Panasonic affiliate), Philips, Silicon Image (now Lattice Semiconductor), Sony, Thomson (now Vantiva), and Toshiba.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Intel contributed the HDCP copy protection system.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The new format won the support of motion picture studios Fox, Universal, Warner Bros. and Disney, along with content distributors DirecTV, EchoStar (Dish Network) and CableLabs.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI founders began development on HDMI 1.0 on April 16, 2002, with the goal of creating an AV connector that was backward-compatible with DVI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] At the time, DVI-HDCP (DVI with HDCP) and DVI-HDTV (DVI-HDCP using the CEA-861-B video standard) were being used on HDTVs.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 was designed to improve on DVI-HDTV by using a smaller connector and adding audio capability, enhanced Y′CBCR capability, and consumer electronics control functions.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The first Authorized Testing Center (ATC), which tests HDMI products, was opened by Silicon Image on June 23, 2003, in California, United States.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The first ATC in Japan was opened by Panasonic on May 1, 2004, in Osaka.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The first ATC in Europe was opened by Philips on May 25, 2005, in Caen, France.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The first ATC in China was opened by Silicon Image on November 21, 2005, in Shenzhen.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The first ATC in India was opened by Philips on June 12, 2008, in Bangalore.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI website contains a list of all the ATCs.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] According to In-Stat, the number of HDMI devices sold was 5 million in 2004, 17.4 million in 2005, 63 million in 2006, and 143 million in 2007.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI has become the de facto standard for HDTVs, and according to In-Stat, around 90% of digital televisions in 2007 included HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In-Stat has estimated that 229 million HDMI devices were sold in 2008.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On April 8, 2008, there were over 850 consumer electronics and PC companies that had adopted the HDMI specification (HDMI adopters).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On January 7, 2009, HDMI Licensing, LLC announced that HDMI had reached an installed base of over 600 million HDMI devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In-Stat estimated that 394 million HDMI devices would sell in 2009 and that all digital televisions by the end of 2009 would have at least one HDMI input.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On January 28, 2008, In-Stat reported that shipments of HDMI were expected to exceed those of DVI in 2008, driven primarily by the consumer electronics market.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In 2008, *PC Magazine* awarded a Technical Excellence Award in the Home Theater category for an "innovation that has changed the world" to the CEC portion of the HDMI specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Ten companies were given a Technology and Engineering Emmy Award for their development of HDMI by the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences on January 7, 2009.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On October 25, 2011, the HDMI Forum was established by the HDMI founders.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Also on the same day HDMI Licensing, LLC announced that there were over 1,100 HDMI adopters and that more than 2 billion HDMI-enabled products had shipped since the launch of the HDMI standard.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On January 8, 2013, HDMI Licensing, LLC announced that there were over 1,300 HDMI adopters and that over 3 billion HDMI devices had shipped since the launch of the HDMI standard.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The day also marked the 10th anniversary of the release of the first HDMI specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] As of January 2021, nearly 10 billion HDMI devices had been sold.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI specification defines the protocols, signals, electrical interfaces and mechanical requirements of the standard.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The maximum pixel clock rate for HDMI 1.0 is 165 MHz, which is sufficient to allow 1080p and WUXGA (1920×1200) at 60 Hz.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.3 increases that to 340 MHz, which allows for higher resolution (such as WQXGA, 2560×1600) across a single digital link.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An HDMI connection can either be single-link (type A/C/D) or dual-link (type B) and can have a video pixel rate of 25 MHz to 340 MHz (for a single-link connection) or 25 MHz to 680 MHz (for a dual-link connection).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Video formats with pixel rates below 25 MHz (like 480i at 13.5 MHz) are transmitted over TMDS links using a pixel-repetition scheme.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI uses the Consumer Technology Association/Electronic Industries Alliance 861 standards.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 to HDMI 1.2a uses the EIA/CEA-861-B video standard, HDMI 1.3 uses the CEA-861-D video standard, and HDMI 1.4 uses the CEA-861-E video standard.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] On July 15, 2013, the CEA announced the publication of CEA-861-F, a standard that can be used by video interfaces such as DVI, HDMI, and LVDS.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] CEA-861-F adds the ability to transmit several Ultra HD video formats and additional color spaces.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] To ensure baseline compatibility between different HDMI sources and displays (as well as backward compatibility with the electrically compatible DVI standard) all HDMI devices must implement the sRGB color space at 8 bits per component.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Ability to use the Y′CBCR color space and higher color depths ("deep color") is optional.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI permits sRGB 4:4:4 chroma sampling (8–16 bits per component), xvYCC 4:4:4 chroma sampling (8–16 bits per component), Y′CBCR 4:4:4 chroma sampling (8–16 bits per component), or Y′CBCR 4:2:2 chroma subsampling (8–12 bits per component).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The color spaces that can be used by HDMI are ITU-R BT.601, ITU-R BT.709-5 and IEC 61966-2-4.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] For digital audio, if an HDMI device has audio, it is required to implement the baseline format: stereo (uncompressed) PCM.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Other formats are optional, with HDMI allowing up to 8 channels of uncompressed audio at sample sizes of 16 bits, 20 bits, or 24 bits, with sample rates of 32 kHz, 44.1 kHz, 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, 96 kHz, 176.4 kHz, or 192 kHz.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI also carries any IEC 61937-compliant compressed audio stream, such as Dolby Digital and DTS, and up to 8 channels of one-bit DSD audio (used on Super Audio CDs) at rates up to four times that of Super Audio CD.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] With version 1.3, HDMI allows lossless compressed audio streams Dolby TrueHD and DTS-HD Master Audio.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] As with the Y′CBCR video, audio capability is optional.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Audio return channel (ARC) is a feature introduced in the HDMI 1.4 standard.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] "Return" refers to the case where the audio comes from the TV and can be sent "upstream" to the AV receiver using the HDMI cable connected to the AV receiver.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An example given on the HDMI website is that a TV that directly receives a terrestrial/satellite broadcast, or has a video source built in, sends the audio "upstream" to the AV receiver.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI standard was not designed to pass closed caption data (for example, subtitles) to the television for decoding.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] As such, any closed caption stream must be decoded and included as an image in the video stream(s) prior to transmission over an HDMI cable to appear on the DTV.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This limits the caption style (even for digital captions) to only that decoded at the source prior to HDMI transmission.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This also prevents closed captions when transmission over HDMI is required for upconversion.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] For example, a DVD player that sends an upscaled 720p/1080i format via HDMI to an HDTV has no way to pass Closed Captioning data so that the HDTV can decode it, as there is no line 21 VBI in that format.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI has three physically separate communication channels, which are the VESA DDC, TMDS and the optional CEC.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The Display Data Channel (DDC) is a VESA standard communications channel based on the I2C bus specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI specifically requires the device implement the Enhanced Display Data Channel (E-DDC), which is used by the HDMI source device to read the E-EDID data from the HDMI sink device to learn what audio/video formats it can take.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI requires that the E-DDC implement I2C standard mode speed (100 kbit/s) and allows it to optionally implement fast mode speed (400 kbit/s).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] I2C address 0x74 on the DDC channel is actively used for High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection (HDCP).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Transition-minimized differential signaling (TMDS) on HDMI interleaves video, audio and auxiliary data using three different packet types, called the video data period, the data island period and the control period.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] During the video data period, the pixels of an active video line are transmitted.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] During the data island period (which occurs during the horizontal and vertical blanking intervals), audio and auxiliary data are transmitted within a series of packets.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The control period occurs between video and data island periods.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Both HDMI and DVI use TMDS to send 10-bit characters that are encoded using 8b/10b encoding that differs from the original IBM form for the video data period and 2b/10b encoding for the control period.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI adds the ability to send audio and auxiliary data using 4b/10b encoding for the data island period.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Each data island period is 32 pixels in size and contains a 32-bit packet header, which includes 8 bits of BCH ECC parity data for error correction and describes the contents of the packet.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Each packet contains four subpackets, and each subpacket is 64 bits in size, including 8 bits of BCH ECC parity data, allowing for each packet to carry up to 224 bits of audio data.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Each data island period can contain up to 18 packets.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Seven of the 15 packet types described in the HDMI 1.3a specifications deal with audio data, while the other 8 types deal with auxiliary data.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Among these are the general control packet and the gamut metadata packet.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The general control packet carries information on AVMUTE (which mutes the audio during changes that may cause audio noise) and color depth (which sends the bit depth of the current video stream and is required for deep color).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The gamut metadata packet carries information on the color space being used for the current video stream and is required for xvYCC.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] CEC also allows for individual CEC-enabled devices to command and control each other without user intervention.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It is a one-wire bidirectional serial bus that is based on the CENELEC standard AV.link protocol to perform remote control functions.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] CEC wiring is mandatory, although implementation of CEC in a product is optional.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It was defined in HDMI Specification 1.0 and updated in HDMI 1.2, HDMI 1.2a and HDMI 1.3a (which added timer and audio commands to the bus).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] USB to CEC adapters exist that allow a computer to control CEC-enabled devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Introduced in HDMI 1.4, HDMI Ethernet and Audio Return Channel (HEAC) adds a high-speed bidirectional data communication link (HEC) and the ability to send audio data upstream to the source device (ARC).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HEAC utilizes two lines from the connector: the previously unused *Reserved* pin (called HEAC+) and the *Hot Plug Detect* pin (called HEAC−).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] If only ARC transmission is required, a single mode signal using the HEAC+ line can be used, otherwise, HEC is transmitted as a differential signal over the pair of lines, and ARC as a common mode component of the pair.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] ARC (Audio Return Channel) is an audio link introduced in 2009 with the HDMI 1.4 standard meant to replace other cables between the TV and the A/V receiver or speaker system.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This direction is used when the TV is the one that generates or receives the video stream instead of the other equipment.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] A typical case is the running of an app on a smart TV such as Netflix, but reproduction of audio is handled by the other equipment.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Without ARC, the audio output from the TV must be routed by another cable, typically TOSLink or RCA, into the speaker system.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] ARC supports stereo PCM, and compressed codecs Dolby Digital, Dolby Digital Plus, and DTS, up to 5.1 channels, with Dolby Atmos metadata in Dolby codecs.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI Ethernet Channel technology consolidates video, audio, and data streams into a single HDMI cable, and the HEC feature enables IP-based applications over HDMI and provides a bidirectional Ethernet communication at 100 Mbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The physical layer of the Ethernet implementation uses a hybrid to simultaneously send and receive attenuated 100BASE-TX-type signals through a single twisted pair.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI is backward compatible with single-link Digital Visual Interface digital video (DVI-D or DVI-I, but not DVI-A or dual-link DVI).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] No signal conversion is required when an adapter or asymmetric cable is used, so there is no loss of video quality.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] From a user's perspective, an HDMI display can be driven by a single-link DVI-D source, since HDMI and DVI-D define an overlapping minimum set of allowed resolutions and frame-buffer formats to ensure a basic level of interoperability.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In the reverse case, a DVI-D monitor has the same level of basic interoperability unless content protection with High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection (HDCP) interferes—or the HDMI color encoding is in component color space Y′CBCR instead of RGB, which is not possible in DVI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An HDMI source, such as a Blu-ray player, may require an HDCP-compliant display, and refuse to output HDCP-protected content to a non-compliant display.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] A further complication is that there is a small amount of display equipment, such as some high-end home theater projectors, designed with HDMI inputs but not HDCP-compliant.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Any DVI-to-HDMI adapter can function as an HDMI-to-DVI adapter (and vice versa).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Typically, the only limitation is the gender of the adapter's connectors and the gender of the cables and sockets it is used with.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Features specific to HDMI, such as remote-control and audio transport, are not available in devices that use legacy DVI-D signalling.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] However, many devices output HDMI over a DVI connector (e.g., ATI HD 2000-series and Nvidia GTX 200-series video cards), and some multimedia displays may accept HDMI (including audio) over a DVI input.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Exact capabilities beyond basic compatibility vary.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection (HDCP) is a newer form of digital rights management (DRM).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Intel created the original technology to make sure that digital content followed the guidelines set by the Digital Content Protection group.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI can use HDCP to encrypt the signal if required by the source device.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Content Scramble System (CSS), Content Protection for Recordable Media (CPRM) and Advanced Access Content System (AACS) require the use of HDCP on HDMI when playing back encrypted DVD Video, DVD Audio, HD DVD and Blu-ray Discs.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDCP repeater bit controls the authentication and switching/distribution of an HDMI signal.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] According to HDCP Specification 1.2 (beginning with HDMI CTS 1.3a), any system that implements HDCP must do so in a fully compliant manner.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDCP testing that was previously only a requirement for optional tests such as the "Simplay HD" testing program is now part of the requirements for HDMI compliance.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDCP accommodates up to 127 connected devices with up to 7 levels, using a combination of sources, sinks and repeaters.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] A simple example of this is several HDMI devices connected to an HDMI AV receiver that is connected to an HDMI display.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Devices called HDCP strippers can remove the HDCP information from the video signal so the video can play on non-HDCP-compliant displays, though a fair use and non-disclosure form must usually be signed with a registering agency before use.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Type A/B are defined in the HDMI 1.0 specification, type C is defined in the HDMI 1.3 specification, and type D/E are defined in the HDMI 1.4 specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The plug (male) connector outside dimensions are 13.9 mm × 4.45 mm, and the receptacle (female) connector inside dimensions are 14 mm × 4.55 mm.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] With the introduction of HDMI 1.3, the maximum bandwidth of single-link HDMI exceeded that of dual-link DVI-D.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] As of HDMI 1.4, the pixel clock rate crossover frequency from single to dual-link has not been defined.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This Mini connector is smaller than the type A plug, measuring 10.42 mm × 2.42 mm but has the same 19-pin configuration.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The differences are that all positive signals of the differential pairs are swapped with their corresponding shield, the DDC/CEC Ground is assigned to pin 13 instead of pin 17, the CEC is assigned to pin 14 instead of pin 13, and the reserved pin is 17 instead of pin 14.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The type C Mini connector can be connected to a type A connector using a type A-to-type C cable.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] For comparison, a micro-USB connector is 6.85 mm × 1.8 mm and a USB type-A connector is 11.5 mm × 4.5 mm.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It keeps the standard 19 pins of types A and C, but the pin assignment is different from both.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The Automotive Connection System has a locking tab to keep the cable from vibrating loose and a shell to help prevent moisture and dirt from corroding the pins.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI alternate mode lets a user connect the reversible USB-C connector with the HDMI source devices (mobile, tablet, laptop).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This cable connects to video display/sink devices using any of the native HDMI connectors.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This is an HDMI cable, in this case a USB-C to HDMI cable.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An HDMI cable is composed of four shielded twisted pairs, with a characteristic impedance of 100 Ω (±15%), plus seven separate conductors.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI cables with Ethernet differ in that three of the separate conductors instead form an additional shielded twisted pair (with the CEC/DDC ground as a shield).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Although no maximum length for an HDMI cable is specified, signal attenuation (dependent on the cable's construction quality and conducting materials) limits usable lengths in practice and certification is difficult to achieve for lengths beyond 13 m.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.3 defines two cable categories: Category 1-certified cables, which have been tested at 74.25 MHz (which would include resolutions such as 720p60 and 1080i60), and Category 2-certified cables, which have been tested at 340 MHz (which would include resolutions such as 1080p60 and 4K30).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Category 1 HDMI cables are marketed as "Standard" and Category 2 HDMI cables as "High Speed".
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This labeling guideline for HDMI cables went into effect on October 17, 2008.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Category 1 and 2 cables can either meet the required parameter specifications for inter-pair skew, far-end crosstalk, attenuation and differential impedance, or they can meet the required non-equalized/equalized eye diagram requirements.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] A cable of about 5 meters (16 feet) can be manufactured to Category 1 specifications easily and inexpensively by using 28 AWG (0.081 mm²) conductors.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] With better quality construction and materials, including 24 AWG (0.205 mm²) conductors, an HDMI cable can reach lengths of up to 15 meters (49 feet).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Many HDMI cables under 5 meters in length that were made before the HDMI 1.3 specification can work as Category 2 cables, but only Category 2-tested cables are guaranteed to work for Category 2 purposes.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI cables are certified to guarantee a certain level of performance at an Authorized Testing Center (ATC).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Separate certifications also exist for "automotive" Standard and High Speed HDMI cables, which use a different connector with a latching mechanism.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Long cables can cause instability of HDCP and blinking on the screen due to the weakened DDC signal that HDCP requires.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An extender can be used to address this instability.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] An HDMI extender is a single device (or pair of devices) powered with an external power source or from the 5 VDC from the HDMI source.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI specification is not an open standard; manufacturers need to be licensed by HDMI LA in order to implement HDMI in any product or component.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Companies that are licensed by HDMI LA are known as HDMI Adopters.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] While earlier versions of HDMI specs are available to the public for download, only adopters have access to the latest standards (HDMI 1.4b/2.1).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Only adopters have access to the compliance test specification (CTS) that is used for compliance and certification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Compliance testing is required before any HDMI product can be legally sold.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The annual fee is due upon the execution of the Adopter Agreement, and must be paid on the anniversary of this date each year thereafter.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The royalty fee structure is the same for all volumes.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Use of HDMI logo requires compliance testing.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Adopters need to license HDCP separately.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI royalty is only payable on licensed products that will be sold on a stand-alone basis (i.e., that are not incorporated into another licensed product that is subject to an HDMI royalty).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] For example, if a cable or IC is sold to an adopter who then includes it in a television subject to a royalty, then the cable or IC maker would not pay a royalty, and the television manufacturer would pay the royalty on the final product.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] If the cable is sold directly to consumers, then the cable would be subject to a royalty.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI devices and cables are designed based on the HDMI Specification, a document published by HDMI Licensing (through version 1.4b) or the HDMI Forum (from version 2.0 onward).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The HDMI Specification defines the minimum baseline requirements that all HDMI devices must adhere to for interoperability, as well as a large set of optional features that HDMI devices may support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The specification is periodically updated to add clarifications or define new capabilities that HDMI devices may implement.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Each new version of the specification expands the list of possible features, but does not mandate support for new features in all devices or establish any "classes" of HDMI products which must support certain capabilities.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Version numbers do not refer to classes or tiers of products with certain levels of feature support, and as such, HDMI specification "version numbers" are not a method of describing support for specific features or describing the capabilities of an HDMI device or cable.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In 2009, HDMI Licensing banned the use of "version numbers" in labeling HDMI products.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Instead, HDMI devices should explicitly declare which features and capabilities they support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] For HDMI cables, a speed rating system was established since feature support is not dependent on the cable (apart from inline Ethernet and ARC); the cable only affects the maximum possible speed of the connection.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI cables should be labeled with the appropriate speed certification (i.e.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Standard Speed, High Speed, or Ultra High Speed), not a "version number".
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 was released on December 9, 2002, and is a single-cable digital audio/video connector interface.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The link architecture is based on DVI, using exactly the same video transmission format but sending audio and other auxiliary data during the blanking intervals of the video stream.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 allows a maximum TMDS clock of 165 MHz (4.95 Gbit/s bandwidth per link), the same as DVI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It defines two connectors called type A and type B, with pinouts based on the Single-Link DVI-D and Dual-Link DVI-D connectors respectively, though the type B connector was never used in any commercial products.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 uses TMDS encoding for video transmission, giving it 3.96 Gbit/s of video bandwidth (1920 × 1080 or 1920 × 1200 at 60 Hz) and 8-channel LPCM/192 kHz/24-bit audio.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 requires support for RGB video, with optional support for Y′CBCR 4:4:4 and 4:2:2 (mandatory if the device has support for Y′CBCR on other interfaces).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Color depth of 10 bpc (30 bit/px) or 12 bpc (36 bit/px) is allowed when using 4:2:2 subsampling, but only 8 bpc (24 bit/px) color depth is permitted when using RGB or Y′CBCR 4:4:4.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0 allows only specific pre-defined video formats, including all the formats defined in EIA/CEA-861-B and some additional formats listed in the HDMI Specification itself.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] All HDMI sources/sinks must also be capable of sending/receiving native Single-Link DVI video and be fully compliant with the DVI Specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.1 was released on May 20, 2004, and added support for DVD-Audio.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.2 was released on August 8, 2005, and added the option of One Bit Audio, used on Super Audio CDs, at up to 8 channels.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] To make HDMI more suitable for use on PC devices, version 1.2 also removed the requirement that only explicitly supported formats be used.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It added the ability for manufacturers to create vendor-specific formats, allowing any arbitrary resolution and refresh rate rather than being limited to a pre-defined list of supported formats.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In addition, it added explicit support for several new formats including 720p at 100 and 120 Hz and relaxed the pixel format support requirements so that sources with only native RGB output (PC sources) would not be required to support Y′CBCR output.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.3 was released on June 22, 2006, and increased the maximum TMDS clock to 340 MHz (10.2 Gbit/s).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Like previous versions, it uses TMDS encoding, giving it a maximum video bandwidth of 8.16 Gbit/s (sufficient for 1920 × 1080 at 144 Hz or 2560 × 1440 at 75 Hz).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It added support for 10 bpc, 12 bpc, and 16 bpc color depth (30, 36, and 48 bit/px), called deep color.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It also added support for the xvYCC color space, in addition to the ITU-R BT.601 and BT.709 color spaces supported by previous versions, and added the ability to carry metadata defining color gamut boundaries.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It also optionally allows output of Dolby TrueHD and DTS-HD Master Audio streams for external decoding by AV receivers.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It incorporates automatic audio syncing (audio video sync) capability.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It defined cable Categories 1 and 2, with Category 1 cable being tested up to 74.25 MHz and Category 2 being tested up to 340 MHz.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It also added the new HDMI type C "Mini" connector for portable devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.4 was released on June 5, 2009, and first came to market after Q2 of 2009.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Retaining the bandwidth of the previous version, HDMI 1.4 defined standardized timings to use for 4096 × 2160 at 24 Hz, 3840 × 2160 at 24, 25, and 30 Hz, and added explicit support for 1920 × 1080 at 120 Hz with CTA-861 timings.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.4 defined several stereoscopic 3D formats including field alternative (interlaced), frame packing (a full resolution top-bottom format), line alternative full, side-by-side half, side-by-side full, 2D + depth, and 2D + depth + graphics + graphics depth (WOWvx).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.4 requires that 3D displays implement the frame packing 3D format at either 720p50 and 1080p24 or 720p60 and 1080p24.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] High Speed HDMI cables as defined in HDMI 1.3 work with all HDMI 1.4 features except for the HDMI Ethernet Channel, which requires the new High Speed HDMI Cable with Ethernet defined in HDMI 1.4.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.0, referred to by some manufacturers as HDMI UHD, was released on September 4, 2013.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.0 increases the maximum bandwidth to 18.0 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.0 uses TMDS encoding for video transmission like previous versions, giving it a maximum video bandwidth of 14.4 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This enables HDMI 2.0 to carry 4K video at 60 Hz with 24 bit/px color depth.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Other features of HDMI 2.0 include support for the Rec.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.1 was officially announced by the HDMI Forum on January 4, 2017, and was released on November 28, 2017.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] It adds support for higher resolutions and higher refresh rates, including 4K 120 Hz and 8K 60 Hz.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.1 also introduces a new HDMI cable category called *Ultra High Speed* (referred to as *48G* during development), which certifies cables at the new higher speeds that these formats require.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Ultra High Speed HDMI cables are backwards compatible with older HDMI devices, and older cables are compatible with new HDMI 2.1 devices, though the full 48 Gbit/s bandwidth is only supported with the new cables.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Some systems may not be able to use HDMI 2.1 because the HDMI Forum is preventing its use in open source implementations (such as Linux open source drivers).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Users of those systems may need to use DisplayPort instead to access high resolutions and speeds.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Video formats that require more bandwidth than 18.0 Gbit/s (4K 60 Hz 8 bpc RGB), such as 4K 60 Hz 10 bpc (HDR), 4K 120 Hz, and 8K 60 Hz, may require the new "Ultra High Speed" or "Ultra High Speed with Ethernet" cables.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.1's other new features are supported with existing HDMI cables.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The increase in maximum bandwidth is achieved by increasing both the bitrate of the data channels and the number of channels.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 2.1 doubles the signaling rate of the data channels to 12 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The structure of the data has been changed to use a new packet-based format with an embedded clock signal, which allows what was formerly the TMDS clock channel to be used as a fourth data channel instead, increasing the signaling rate across that channel to 12 Gbit/s as well.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] These changes increase the aggregate bandwidth from 18.0 Gbit/s (3 × 6.0 Gbit/s) to 48.0 Gbit/s (4 × 12.0 Gbit/s), a 2.66× improvement in bandwidth.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] In addition, the data is transmitted more efficiently by using a 16b/18b encoding scheme, which uses a larger percentage of the bandwidth for data rather than DC balancing compared to the TMDS scheme used by previous versions (88.8% compared to 80%).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This, in combination with the 2.66× bandwidth, raises the maximum data rate of HDMI 2.1 from 14.4 Gbit/s to 42.6 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Subtracting overhead for FEC, the usable data rate is approximately 42.0 Gbit/s, around 2.92× the data rate of HDMI 2.0.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The 48 Gbit/s bandwidth provided by HDMI 2.1 is enough for 8K resolution at approximately 50 Hz, with 8 bpc RGB or Y′CBCR 4:4:4 color.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] To achieve even higher formats, HDMI 2.1 can use Display Stream Compression (DSC) with a compression ratio of up to 3∶1.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Using Y′CBCR with 4:2:2 or 4:2:0 chroma subsampling in combination with DSC can allow for even higher formats.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Some of the transmitted bits are used for encoding purposes rather than representing data, so the rate at which video data can be transmitted across the HDMI interface is only a portion of the total bit rate.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] The TMDS character rate is the number of 10-bit TMDS characters per second transmitted across one HDMI data channel.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] This is sometimes informally referred to as the pixel clock or TMDS clock because these terms were once equivalent in past HDMI versions.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] TMDS encoding uses 10 bits of the transmission to send 8 bits of data, so only 80% of the transmission bit rate is available for data throughput.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] 16b/18b encoding uses 18 bits of bandwidth to send 16 bits of data, so 88.8% of the transmission bit rate is available for data throughput.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] HDMI 1.0–1.2a permit 10 bpc and 12 bpc color depth only when Y′CBCR 4:2:2 color format is used.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] When using RGB or Y′CBCR 4:4:4, only 8 bpc color is permitted.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Able to represent out-of-gamut colors à la xvYCC.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p01] Adobe RGB with BT.601 matrix, defined in IEC 61966-2-5 Annex A.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The maximum limits for TMDS transmission are calculated using standard data rate calculations.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] For FRL transmission, the limits are calculated using the capacity computation algorithm provided by the HDMI Specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] All calculations assume uncompressed RGB video with CVT-RB v2 timing.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Maximum limits may differ if compression (i.e.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DSC) or Y′CBCR 4:2:0 chroma subsampling are used.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Display manufacturers may also use non-standard blanking intervals (a Vendor-Specific Timing Format as defined in the HDMI Specification) rather than CVT-RB v2 to achieve even higher frequencies when bandwidth is a constraint.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The refresh frequencies in the below table do not represent the absolute maximum limit of each interface, but rather an estimate based on a modern standardized timing formula.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The minimum blanking intervals (and therefore the exact maximum frequency that can be achieved) will depend on the display and how many secondary data packets it requires, and therefore will differ from model to model.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] HDMI 1.0 and 1.1 are restricted to transmitting only certain video formats, defined in EIA/CEA-861-B and in the HDMI Specification itself.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] HDMI 1.2 and all later versions allow any arbitrary resolution and frame rate (within the bandwidth limit).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Formats that are not supported by the HDMI Specification (i.e., no standardized timings defined) may be implemented as a vendor-specific format.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Successive versions of the HDMI Specification continue to add support for additional formats (such as 4K resolutions), but the added support is to establish standardized timings to ensure interoperability between products, not to establish which formats are or are not permitted.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Video formats do not require explicit support from the HDMI Specification in order to be transmitted and displayed.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Individual products may have heavier limitations than those listed below, since HDMI devices are not required to support the maximum bandwidth of the HDMI version that they implement.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Therefore, it is not guaranteed that a display will support the refresh rates listed in this table, even if the display has the required HDMI version.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Uncompressed 8 bpc (24 bit/px) color depth and RGB or Y′CBCR 4:4:4 color format are assumed on this table except where noted.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Standard HDMI cable certification (Category 1) only tests up to 74.25 MHz (2.2275 Gbit/s).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Therefore only High Speed HDMI cables or above are rated for the maximum allowed speed, even for versions that predate the introduction of the High Speed certification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] HDR10 requires 10 bpc (30 bit/px) color depth, which uses 25% more bandwidth than standard 8 bpc video.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Uncompressed 10 bpc color depth and RGB or Y′CBCR 4:4:4 color format are assumed on this table except where noted.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The features defined in the HDMI specification that an HDMI device may implement are listed below.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] For historical interest, the version of the HDMI specification in which the feature was first added is also listed.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] All features of the HDMI specification are optional; HDMI devices may implement any combination of these features.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Although the "HDMI version numbers" are commonly misused as a way of indicating that a device supports certain features, this notation has no official meaning and is considered improper by HDMI Licensing.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] There is no officially defined correlation between features supported by a device and any claimed "version numbers", as version numbers refer to historical editions of the HDMI specification document, not to particular classes of HDMI devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Manufacturers are forbidden from describing their devices using HDMI version numbers, and are required to identify support for features by listing explicit support for them, but the HDMI forum has received criticism for lack of enforcement of these policies.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Large number of additions and clarifications for CEC commands.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] One addition is CEC command, allowing for volume control of an AV receiver.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Blu-ray Disc and HD DVD, introduced in 2006, offer high-fidelity audio features that require HDMI for best results.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] HDMI 1.3 can transport Dolby Digital Plus, Dolby TrueHD, and DTS-HD Master Audio bitstreams in compressed form.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] This capability allows for an AV receiver with the necessary decoder to decode the compressed audio stream.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Blu-ray specification does not include video encoded with either deep color or xvYCC; thus, HDMI 1.0 can transfer Blu-ray discs at full video quality.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The HDMI 1.4 specification (released in 2009) added support for 3D video and is used by all Blu-ray 3D compatible players.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Blu-ray Disc Association (BDA) spokespersons have stated (Sept.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] 2014 at IFA show in Berlin, Germany) that the Blu-ray, Ultra HD players, and 4K discs are expected to be available starting in the second half to 2015.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] It is anticipated that such Blu-ray UHD players will be required to include a HDMI 2.0 output that supports HDCP 2.2.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Blu-ray permits secondary audio decoding, whereby the disc content can tell the player to mix multiple audio sources together before final output.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Some Blu-ray and HD DVD players can decode all of the audio codecs internally and can output LPCM audio over HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Multichannel LPCM can be transported over an HDMI connection, and as long as the AV receiver implements multichannel LPCM audio over HDMI and implements HDCP, the audio reproduction is equal in resolution to HDMI 1.3 bitstream output.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Some low-cost AV receivers, such as the Onkyo TX-SR506, do not allow audio processing over HDMI and are labelled as "HDMI pass through" devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Virtually all modern AV Receivers now offer HDMI 1.4 inputs and outputs with processing for all of the audio formats offered by Blu-ray Discs and other HD video sources.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] During 2014 several manufacturers introduced premium AV Receivers that include one, or multiple, HDMI 2.0 inputs along with a HDMI 2.0 output(s).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] However, not until 2015 did most major manufacturers of AV receivers also support HDCP 2.2 as needed to support certain high quality UHD video sources, such as Blu-ray UHD players.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Most consumer camcorders, as well as many digital cameras, are equipped with a mini-HDMI connector (type C connector).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] In addition, to be used as a video source, such as for streaming or switching, the camera must also be capable of removing the UI elements from the image.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Therefore, usable uncompressed video out of HDMI without the device's UI elements is often called "clean HDMI".
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Personal computers (PCs) with a DVI interface are capable of video output to an HDMI-enabled monitor.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Some PCs include an HDMI interface and may also be capable of HDMI audio output, depending on specific hardware.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] For example, Intel's motherboard chipsets since the 945G and NVIDIA's GeForce 8200/8300 motherboard chipsets are capable of 8-channel LPCM output over HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Eight-channel LPCM audio output over HDMI with a video card was first seen with the ATI Radeon HD 4850, which was released in June 2008 and is implemented by other video cards in the ATI Radeon HD 4000 series.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Linux can drive 8-channel LPCM audio over HDMI if the video card has the necessary hardware and implements the Advanced Linux Sound Architecture (ALSA).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The ATI Radeon HD 4000 series implements ALSA.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Cyberlink announced in June 2008 that they would update their PowerDVD playback software to allow 192 kHz/24-bit Blu-ray Disc audio decoding in Q3-Q4 of 2008.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Corel's WinDVD 9 Plus currently has 96 kHz/24-bit Blu-ray Disc audio decoding.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Even with an HDMI output, a computer may not be able to produce signals that implement HDCP, Microsoft's Protected Video Path, or Microsoft's Protected Audio Path.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Several early graphic cards were labelled as "HDCP-enabled" but did not have the hardware needed for HDCP; this included some graphic cards based on the ATI X1600 chipset and certain models of the NVIDIA Geforce 7900 series.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The first computer monitors that could process HDCP were released in 2005; by February 2006 a dozen different models had been released.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Protected Video Path was enabled in graphic cards that had HDCP capability, since it was required for output of Blu-ray Disc and HD DVD video.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] In comparison, the Protected Audio Path was required only if a lossless audio bitstream (such as Dolby TrueHD or DTS-HD MA) was output.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Uncompressed LPCM audio, however, does not require a Protected Audio Path, and software programs such as PowerDVD and WinDVD can decode Dolby TrueHD and DTS-HD MA and output it as LPCM.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] A limitation is that if the computer does not implement a Protected Audio Path, the audio must be downsampled to 16-bit 48 kHz but can still output at up to 8 channels.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] No graphic cards were released in 2008 that implemented the Protected Audio Path.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Asus Xonar HDAV1.3 became the first HDMI sound card that implemented the Protected Audio Path and could both bitstream and decode lossless audio (Dolby TrueHD and DTS-HD MA), although bitstreaming is only available if using the ArcSoft TotalMedia Theatre software.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] It has an HDMI 1.3 input/output, and Asus says that it can work with most video cards on the market.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The ATI Radeon HD 5870 released in September 2009 is the first video card that allows bitstream output over HDMI for Dolby TrueHD and DTS-HD Master Audio.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The AMD Radeon HD 6000 series implements HDMI 1.4a.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The AMD Radeon HD 7000 series implements HDMI 1.4b.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] In December 2010, it was announced that several computer vendors and display makers including Intel, AMD, Dell, Lenovo, Samsung, and LG would stop using LVDS (actually, FPD-Link) from 2013 and legacy DVI and VGA connectors from 2015, replacing them with DisplayPort and HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On August 27, 2012, Asus announced a new 27 in (69 cm) monitor that produces its native resolution of 2560×1440 via HDMI 1.4.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On September 18, 2014, Nvidia launched GeForce GTX 980 and GTX 970 (with GM204 chip) with HDMI 2.0 support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On January 22, 2015, GeForce GTX 960 (with GM206 chip) launched with HDMI 2.0 support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On March 17, 2015, GeForce GTX TITAN X (GM200) launched with HDMI 2.0 support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On June 1, 2015, GeForce GTX 980 Ti (with GM200 chip) launched with HDMI 2.0 support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On August 20, 2015, GeForce GTX 950 (with GM206 chip) launched with HDMI 2.0 support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On May 6, 2016, Nvidia launched the GeForce GTX 1080 (GP104 GPU) with HDMI 2.0b support.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On September 1, 2020, Nvidia launched the GeForce RTX 30 series, the world's first discrete graphics cards with support for the full 48 Gbit/s bandwidth with Display Stream Compression 1.2 of HDMI 2.1.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Beginning with the seventh generation of video game consoles, most consoles support HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Some tablet computers implement HDMI using Micro-HDMI (type D) port, while others like the Eee Pad Transformer implement the standard using mini-HDMI (type C) ports.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] All iPad models have a special A/V adapter that converts Apple's Lightning connector to a standard HDMI (type A) port.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Samsung has a similar proprietary thirty-pin port for their Galaxy Tab 10.1 that could adapt to HDMI as well as USB drives.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Dell Streak 5 smartphone/tablet hybrid is capable of outputting over HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] While the Streak uses a PDMI port, a separate cradle adds HDMI compatibility.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Some tablets running Android OS provide HDMI output using a mini-HDMI (type C) port.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Most new laptops and desktops now have built in HDMI as well.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Many mobile phones can produce an output of HDMI video via a micro-HDMI connector, SlimPort, MHL or other adapter.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Cables are available that contain the necessary electronics, but it is important to distinguish these *active* converter cables from *passive* HDMI to VGA cables (which are typically cheaper as they don't include any electronics).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The passive cables are *only* useful if a user has a device that is generating or expecting HDMI signals on a VGA connector, or VGA signals on an HDMI connector; this is a non-standard feature, not implemented by most devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The HDMI Alternate Mode for USB-C allows HDMI-enabled sources with a USB-C connector to directly connect to standard HDMI display devices, without requiring an adapter.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The standard was released in September 2016, and supports all HDMI 1.4b features such as video resolutions up to Ultra HD 30 Hz and CEC.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Previously, the similar DisplayPort Alternate Mode could be used to connect to HDMI displays from USB Type-C sources, but where in that case active adapters were required to convert from DisplayPort to HDMI, HDMI Alternate Mode connects to the display natively.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Alternate Mode reconfigures the four SuperSpeed differential pairs present in USB-C to carry the three HDMI TMDS channels and the clock signal.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The two Sideband Use pins (SBU1 and SBU2) are used to carry the HDMI Ethernet and Audio Return Channel and the Hot Plug Detect functionality (HEAC+/Utility pin and HEAC−/HPD pin).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] As stated at CES in January 2023, HDMI Alternate Mode for USB Type-C is no longer being updated as there are no known products using this protocol, reducing its relevance in the current market.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] This will reduce consumer confusion as DisplayPort Alternate Mode is the primary video protocol of choice over USB-C.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The DisplayPort audio/video interface was introduced in May 2006 by the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] In recent years, DisplayPort connectors have become a common feature of premium products—displays, desktop computers, and video cards; most of the companies producing DisplayPort equipment are in the computer sector.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The DisplayPort website states that DisplayPort is expected to complement HDMI, but as of 2016 100% of HD and UHD TVs had HDMI connectivity.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort supported some advanced features which are useful for multimedia content creators and gamers (e.g., 5K, Adaptive-Sync), which was the reason most GPUs have DisplayPort.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] These features were added to the official HDMI specification slightly later, but with the introduction of HDMI 2.1, these gaps are already leveled off (e.g., VRR / Variable Refresh Rate).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort uses a self-clocking, micro-packet-based protocol that allows for a variable number of differential pair lanes as well as flexible allocation of bandwidth between audio and video, and allows encapsulating multi-channel compressed audio formats in the audio stream.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort 1.2 supports multiple audio/video streams, variable refresh rate (FreeSync), and Dual-mode transmitters compatible with HDMI 1.2 or 1.4.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Revision 1.3 increases overall transmission bandwidth to 32.4 Gbit/s with the new HBR3 mode featuring 8.1 Gbit/s per lane; it requires Dual-mode with mandatory HDMI 2.0 compatibility and HDCP 2.2.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Revision 1.4 added Display Stream Compression (DSC), support for the BT.2020 color space, and HDR10 extensions from CTA-861.3, including static and dynamic metadata.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Revision 1.4a was published in April 2018, updating DisplayPort's DSC implementation from 1.2 to 1.2a.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Revision 2.0 increased overall bandwidth from 25.92 to 77.37 Gbit/s, enabling increased resolutions and refresh rates, increasing the resolutions and refresh rates with HDR support, and other related improvements.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The DisplayPort features an adapter detection mechanism enabling dual-mode operation and the transmission of TMDS signals allowing the conversion to DVI and HDMI 1.2/1.4/2.0 signals using a passive adapter.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The same external connector is used for both protocols – when a DVI/HDMI passive adapter is attached, the transmitter circuit switches to TMDS mode.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort Dual-mode ports and cables/adapters are typically marked with the DisplayPort++ logo.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Thunderbolt ports with mDP connector also supports Dual-mode passive HDMI adapters/cables.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Conversion to dual-link DVI and component video (VGA/YPbPr) requires active powered adapters.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The USB 3.1 type-C connector is increasingly the standard video connector, replacing legacy video connectors such as mDP, Thunderbolt, HDMI, and VGA in mobile devices.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] USB-C connectors can transmit DisplayPort video to docks and displays using standard USB type-C cables or type-C to DisplayPort cables and adapters; USB-C also supports HDMI adapters that actively convert from DisplayPort to HDMI 1.4 or 2.0.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort Alternate Mode for USB type-C specification was published in 2015.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] USB type-C chipsets are not required to include Dual-mode, so passive DP-HDMI adapters do not work with type-C sources.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] A specification for "HDMI Alternate Mode for USB type-C" was released in 2016, but was discontinued in 2023, with HDMI Licensing Administration stating they knew of no adapter having ever been produced.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] DisplayPort is royalty-free, though patent pool administrator Via-LA attempts to collect a $0.20 per-device charge for a bulk license to patents it regards as essential to the DisplayPort specification, while HDMI has an annual fee of US$10,000 and a per unit royalty rate of between $0.04 and $0.15.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] HDMI has had a few advantages over DisplayPort, such as ability to carry Consumer Electronics Control (CEC) signals since its first generation (DisplayPort 1.3, introduced in 2014, is the earliest DisplayPort generation which can carry CEC signals).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Mobile High-Definition Link (MHL) is an adaptation of HDMI intended to connect mobile devices such as smartphones and tablets to high-definition televisions (HDTVs) and displays.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Unlike DVI, which is compatible with HDMI using only passive cables and adapters, MHL requires that the HDMI socket be MHL-enabled, otherwise an active adapter (or dongle) is required to convert the signal to HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] MHL is developed by a consortium of five consumer electronics manufacturers, several of which are also behind HDMI.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] MHL pares down the three TMDS channels in a standard HDMI connection to a single one running over any connector that provides at least five pins.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] This lets existing connectors in mobile devices – such as micro-USB – be used, avoiding the need for additional dedicated video output sockets.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The USB port switches to MHL mode when it detects a compatible device is connected.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] In addition to the features in common with HDMI (such as HDCP encrypted uncompressed high-definition video and eight-channel surround sound), MHL also adds the provision of power charging for the mobile device while in use, and also enables the TV remote to control it.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Although support for these additional features requires connection to an MHL-enabled HDMI port, power charging can also be provided when using active MHL to HDMI adapters (connected to standard HDMI ports), provided there is a separate power connection to the adapter.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Like HDMI, MHL defines a USB-C Alternate Mode to support the MHL standard over USB-C connections.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Version 1.0 supported 720p/1080i 60 Hz (RGB/4:4:4 pixel encoding) with a bandwidth of 2.25 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Versions 1.3 and 2.0 added support for 1080p 60 Hz (Y′CBCR 4:2:2) with a bandwidth of 3 Gbit/s in PackedPixel mode.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Version 3.0 increased the bandwidth to 6 Gbit/s to support Ultra HD (3840 × 2160) 30 Hz video, and also changed from being frame-based, like HDMI, to packet-based.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The fourth version, superMHL, increased bandwidth by operating over multiple TMDS differential pairs (up to a total of six) allowing a maximum of 36 Gbit/s.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The six lanes are supported over a reversible 32-pin superMHL connector, while four lanes are supported over USB-C Alternate Mode (only a single lane is supported over micro-USB/HDMI).
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] Display Stream Compression (DSC) is used to allow up to 8K Ultra HD (7680 × 4320) 120 Hz HDR video, and to support Ultra HD 60 Hz video over a single lane.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] On October 25, 2011, the HDMI Forum was established by the HDMI founders to create an open, nonprofit industry consortium so that interested companies can participate in the development of the HDMI specification.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] All members of the HDMI Forum have equal voting rights, may participate in the Technical Working Group, and if elected can be on the Board of Directors.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] There is no limit to the number of companies allowed in the HDMI Forum though companies must pay an annual fee of US$15,000 with an additional annual fee of $5,000 for those companies that serve on the Board of Directors.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] The Board of Directors is made up of 11 companies who are elected every two years by a general vote of HDMI Forum members.
[src:hdmi/hdmi-p02] All future developments of the HDMI specification take place in the HDMI Forum and are built upon the HDMI 1.4b specification.
